), if I’m not too exhausted. That’s how I ended every invitation these days, a safety net I wove for myself. I didn’t expect anyone to call me out on it, but tonight, Maya did. She replied: “Come even if you are.”

So I did. I dragged my weary self across the city, past flickering streetlights and cats prowling for scraps. Maya’s apartment glowed gold from a single lamp in the window, the kind of light that promises warmth. She opened the door before I knocked, her smile so bright it made me forget my aches.

We sat on her worn couch, a blanket wrapped around our knees. She poured tea, and we talked about everything except why I was tired. By the time the sun hinted at the horizon, the exhaustion had faded, replaced by the quiet certainty that sometimes, you just have to show up. Even when you think you can’t.

), if I’m not too exhausted. That’s the agreement I make with myself every evening before the city lights flicker on. I trace the outline of the envelope in my pocket, the one I promised to deliver. The streets below buzz with activity, neon reflections in puddles, but I linger on the rooftop, counting the beats of my heart.

Finally, I descend. My feet echo on the stairs, the envelope heavy in my hand. At the corner, I spot her—leaning against the lamppost, a strand of hair caught in the wind. She sees me, her eyes searching for something familiar. I offer the envelope, tentative.

“For you,” I say, voice thin with fatigue. She smiles, takes it, and tucks it into her coat. No words needed. Sometimes, even exhaustion can’t keep us from what matters.

), if I’m not too exhausted. It’s a phrase I use to excuse my unpredictability, to shield myself from disappointment—both mine and theirs. Tonight, I scrolled past the text I’d written to my brother, asking if he wanted to meet at the late-night diner, but hesitated before sending. The weight of the week pressed on me, but so did the memory of our last conversation, laughter echoing over greasy fries.

With a sigh, I pressed send. The reply came quickly: “I’ll be there.”

So I grabbed my coat and stepped into the night, letting the crisp air sting my cheeks awake. As I walked, I realized that sometimes, pushing beyond exhaustion is a love letter, a promise that even when I’m tired, you matter. When I saw him waiting in the neon glow, I knew I’d made the right choice.
